===Etymology===
First attested in the 17th century, noun use of 5th century {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|oxymorum|oxymōrum|pos=adj}}, neut. nom. form of {{m|la|oxymorus|oxymōrus|pos=adj}},<ref name="L+S">{{R:L&S|1=oxymōrus|2=oxymorus}}</ref> from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|ὀξύμωρος||}}, compound of {{m|grc|ὀξύς||sharp, keen, pointed}}<ref>{{R:LSJ|1=o)cu/s2|w=ὀξύς}}</ref> (English {{m|en|oxy-}}, as in {{m|en|oxygen}}) + {{m|grc|μωρός||dull, stupid, foolish}}<ref>{{R:LSJ|1=mwro/s|w=μωρός}}</ref> (English {{m|en|moron||stupid person}}). Literally "sharp-dull", "keen-stupid", or "pointed-foolish"<ref name="LSJ">{{R:LSJ|1=o)cu/mwros|w=ὀξύμωρος}}</ref> – itself an '''oxymoron''', hence [[autological]]; compare {{m|en|sophomore|lit=wise fool}}, influenced by similar analysis. The compound form {{m|grc|ὀξύμωρον}} is not found in the extant Ancient Greek sources.<ref>[http://dictionary.oed.com/cgi/entry/50168789 OED]</ref>

