===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|oxymora}}

# A [[figure of speech]] in which two words or phrases with opposing meanings are used together intentionally for effect.
# {{lb|en|loosely}} A [[contradiction in terms]].

====Usage notes====
* Historically, an {{m|en||oxymoron}} was "a {{m|en|paradox}} with a point",<ref>Jebb, Sir Richard (1900). ''[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0023:text=comm:commline=74&highlight=o%29cu%2Fmwron Sophocles: The Plays and Fragments, with critical notes, commentary, and translation in English prose. Part III: The Antigone]''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</ref> or "pointedly foolish: a witty saying, the more pointed from being paradoxical or seemingly absurd" at first glance.<ref name="LSJ" /> Its deliberate purpose was to underscore a point or to draw attention to a concealed point. The common {{l|en|vernacular}} use of {{m|en||oxymoron}} as simply a [[contradiction in terms]] is considered incorrect by some speakers and writers, and is perhaps best avoided in certain contexts.<ref name="L+S" />

